METHODOLOGY

Image Collection

Here, we need to incorporate the ability to select and process CCTV images. However, for this notebook, we will simply load a sample image.

  • The code sets the cache directory for the transformers library.
  • It imports necessary libraries, including classes for object detection and image processing from the transformers library.
  • The code specifies the image to be processed and opens it using the Python Imaging Library (PIL).
  • The pre-trained object detection model (YolosForObjectDetection) and image processor (YolosImageProcessor) are loaded.
  • The image is processed by the YolosImageProcessor to create a tensor that is fed into the object detection model.
  • The model generates outputs, including logits (raw, unnormalized output of the last layer of the model) and predicted bounding boxes for objects detected in the image.
  • The object detection results are post-processed by applying a confidence threshold (0.9 in this case) and resizing the bounding boxes back to the original image size.
  • Finally, the code prints the class, confidence score, and location (bounding box) of each detected object.

import os
os.environ['XDG_CACHE_HOME'] = '/home/msds2023/fcamarao/.cache'

from transformers import YolosImageProcessor, YolosForObjectDetection
from PIL import Image
from IPython.display import display
import numpy as np
import torch
import requests
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import matplotlib.patches as patches
from transformers import (AutoFeatureExtractor,
                          SegformerForSemanticSegmentation)
import torch.nn as nn
import cv2



image_path = 'data/sample1.jpg'
main_image = Image.open(image_path)

model_person = YolosForObjectDetection.from_pretrained('hustvl/yolos-tiny')
image_processor = YolosImageProcessor.from_pretrained("hustvl/yolos-tiny")

inputs = image_processor(images=main_image, return_tensors="pt")
outputs = model_person(**inputs)

# model predicts bounding boxes and corresponding COCO classes
logits = outputs.logits
bboxes = outputs.pred_boxes

# print results
target_sizes = torch.tensor([main_image.size[::-1]])
results = image_processor.post_process_object_detection(
    outputs, threshold=0.9, target_sizes=target_sizes)[0]
for score, label, box in zip(results["scores"],
                             results["labels"], results["boxes"]):
    box = [round(i, 2) for i in box.tolist()]
    print(
        f"Detected {model_person.config.id2label[label.item()]} "
        f"with confidence "
        f"{round(score.item(), 3)} at location {box}"
    )

Object Detection

  • The code creates a figure and axes for displaying the image using matplotlib.
  • It displays the original image on the created axes.
  • An empty list is initialized to store bounding box values.
  • The code iterates through the object detection results (scores, labels, boxes). For each detected object:
    • If the label of the detected object is 'person', the code processes the bounding box.
    • The bounding box's coordinates are rounded to two decimal places and printed, along with the object's label and the confidence score.
    • These bounding box values are stored in the list.
    • The color for the bounding box is set to red.
    • A rectangular patch is created with the bounding box dimensions and color, representing the detected person in the image.
    • This patch is added to the axes.
  • Finally, the updated figure, with bounding boxes for detected persons, is displayed.

# Create figure and axes
fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(12, 6))

# Display the image
ax.imshow(main_image)

bounding_boxes = []  # List to store bounding box values

# Create bounding boxes
for score, label, box in zip(results["scores"],
                             results["labels"], results["boxes"]):
    # Get the label name
    label_name = model_person.config.id2label[label.item()]
    # Only process the bounding boxes for 'person'
    if label_name == 'person':
        box = [round(i, 2) for i in box.tolist()]
        print(
            f"Detected {label_name} with confidence "
            f"{round(score.item(), 3)} at location {box}"
        )
        # Store bounding box values in the list
        bounding_boxes.append(box)

        # Set default color for bounding box and count label
        bbox_color = 'red'

        # Create a Rectangle patch with the modified color
        rect = patches.Rectangle((box[0], box[1]), box[2]-box[0], box[3] -
                                 box[1], linewidth=1,
                                 edgecolor=bbox_color, facecolor='none')
        # Add the patch to the Axes
        ax.add_patch(rect)

filename = os.path.splitext(os.path.basename(image_path))[0]
# Crop and save the bounding boxes as separate images
for i, box in enumerate(bounding_boxes):
    # Convert box values to integers
    box = [int(coord) for coord in box]

    # Crop the image using the bounding box coordinates
    cropped_image = main_image.crop(box)

    # Save the cropped image with a unique filename
    cropped_image.save(f"data/cropped_images/{filename}_{i}.jpg")

Semantic Segmentation

In this case, I have applied semantic segmentation to identify specific objects segmented from the person. I then utilized masking to isolate these objects within the image.

  • The code loads a feature extractor and a semantic segmentation model using the AutoFeatureExtractor and SegformerForSemanticSegmentation classes from the transformers library.
  • It defines a dictionary mapping class indices to labels for different parts of a person's clothing and accessories.
  • The path to the directory containing the cropped images of detected persons is specified.
  • The code lists all the image files in the directory that correspond to a particular person (identified by a filename prefix).
  • For each cropped image of the person:
    • The image is opened and processed by the feature extractor to create a tensor.
    • This tensor is fed into the semantic segmentation model, which generates logits (raw, unnormalized output of the last layer of the model).
    • The logits are upsampled to match the original image size, and the class with the maximum logit value for each pixel is considered as the predicted class.
    • The original image and the predicted segmentation mask are displayed side by side.
    • The predicted segmentation mask is converted to a numpy array, and the unique classes present in the mask are identified along with their counts.
    • The logits are upsampled again to a fixed size (128x128), and the softmax function is applied to compute probabilities for each class.
    • The class with the maximum probability for each pixel is considered as the predicted class, and the corresponding probability values are extracted.
    • The average probability (confidence) for each unique class present in the segmentation mask is computed and printed.
In [5]:
# Load the feature extractor and segmentation model
extractor = AutoFeatureExtractor.from_pretrained(
    "mattmdjaga/segformer_b2_clothes")
model_segment = SegformerForSemanticSegmentation.from_pretrained(
    "mattmdjaga/segformer_b2_clothes")

# Map of class indices to labels
id2label = {
    0: "Background",
    1: "Hat",
    2: "Hair",
    3: "Sunglasses",
    4: "Upper-clothes",
    5: "Skirt",
    6: "Pants",
    7: "Dress",
    8: "Belt",
    9: "Left-shoe",
    10: "Right-shoe",
    11: "Face",
    12: "Left-leg",
    13: "Right-leg",
    14: "Left-arm",
    15: "Right-arm",
    16: "Bag",
    17: "Scarf",
}

# Define the directory path containing the images
image_path_2 = "data/cropped_images"

# Specify the prefix
prefix = filename + "_"

# Get the list of image files in the directory
image_files = [file for file in os.listdir(
    image_path_2) if file.startswith(prefix)]

# Iterate over each image file in the directory
for file_name in image_files:
    file_path = os.path.join(image_path_2, file_name)
    image = Image.open(file_path)  # Load the image

    # Process the image
    inputs = extractor(images=image, return_tensors="pt")

    outputs = model_segment(**inputs)
    logits = outputs.logits.cpu()

    upsampled_logits = nn.functional.interpolate(
        logits,
        size=image.size[::-1],
        mode="bilinear",
        align_corners=False,
    )

    pred_seg = upsampled_logits.argmax(dim=1)[0]

    # Display the image and the predicted segmentation mask
    fig, axes = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize=(12, 6))

    # Display the original image
    axes[0].imshow(image)
    axes[0].set_title("Original Image")
    axes[0].axis("off")

    # Display the predicted segmentation mask
    axes[1].imshow(pred_seg, cmap="gray")
    axes[1].set_title("Segmentation Mask")
    axes[1].axis("off")

    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

    # Convert to numpy array
    pred_seg_np = pred_seg.detach().numpy()

    # Count unique class indices
    unique, counts = np.unique(pred_seg_np, return_counts=True)

    upsampled_logits = nn.functional.interpolate(
        logits,
        size=(128, 128),  # Set the size directly
        mode="bilinear",
        align_corners=False,
    )

    # Compute softmax probabilities
    softmax_logits = torch.nn.functional.softmax(upsampled_logits, dim=1)

    # Get the probabilities of the predicted classes
    probabilities = softmax_logits.max(dim=1).values.squeeze()

    # Convert to numpy array
    probabilities_np = probabilities.detach().numpy()

    # Get the segmentation prediction
    pred_seg = upsampled_logits.argmax(dim=1)

    # Convert to numpy array
    pred_seg_np = pred_seg.squeeze().detach().numpy()

    # Print average probability (confidence) for each class
    for u in np.unique(pred_seg_np):
        average_probability = probabilities_np[pred_seg_np == u].mean()
        print(
            f"Average confidence for "
            f"{id2label[u]}: {average_probability:.3f}")

Object and Color Segmentation Classification

  • The code specifies certain parameters like the target label ("Upper-clothes"), the average probability threshold (0.6), the required percentage (15%), and the target color ("red").
  • It then initializes an empty list outputted_images to store the file names of the images that meet the specified conditions.
  • For each image in the directory:
    • The image is loaded and processed using the feature extractor and segmentation model.
    • The softmax probabilities of the predicted classes are computed.
    • The segmentation prediction is obtained by finding the class with the maximum probability for each pixel in the image.
    • The code then checks if the average probability of the target label is greater than the specified probability threshold.
    • If the condition is met, the code creates a mask for the target label using the cv2.inRange function. This function checks if array elements lie between the elements of two other arrays (in this case, the lower and upper range of the target color in the HSV color space).
    • The original image is then converted to HSV color space using the cv2.cvtColor function.
    • The color mask is applied to the target label region of the segmentation mask.
    • The code then checks if the color-filtered region constitutes a certain percentage of the total region of the target label. - If it does, the original image, the target label, and the color filtered segmentation mask are displayed, and the file name of the image is added to the outputted_images list.
  • After all images have been processed, the code extracts the numeric values from the file names in the utputted_images list and stores them in a separate list numeric_values.

# Specify the label and average probability threshold
target_label = "Upper-clothes"
probability_threshold = 0.6
required_percentage = 15  # 10%

# Specify the target color
target_color = "red"

# List to store the file names of outputted images
outputted_images = []

# Iterate over each image file in the directory
for file_name in image_files:
    file_path = os.path.join(image_path_2, file_name)
    image = Image.open(file_path)  # Load the image

    # Process the image
    inputs = extractor(images=image, return_tensors="pt")

    outputs = model_segment(**inputs)
    logits = outputs.logits.cpu()

    upsampled_logits = nn.functional.interpolate(
        logits,
        size=image.size[::-1],
        mode="bilinear",
        align_corners=False,
    )

    # Compute softmax probabilities
    softmax_logits = torch.nn.functional.softmax(upsampled_logits, dim=1)

    # Get the probabilities of the predicted classes
    probabilities = softmax_logits.max(dim=1).values.squeeze()

    # Convert to numpy array
    probabilities_np = probabilities.detach().cpu().numpy()

    # Get the segmentation prediction
    pred_seg = upsampled_logits.argmax(dim=1)

    # Convert to numpy array
    pred_seg_np = pred_seg.squeeze().detach().cpu().numpy()

    # Filter image based on label and average probability threshold
    label_index = list(id2label.values()).index(target_label)
    average_probability = probabilities_np[pred_seg_np == label_index].mean()

    if average_probability > probability_threshold:
        # Convert pred_seg_np to uint8 for imshow()
        pred_seg_np = pred_seg_np.astype(np.uint8)

        # Convert the original image to HSV
        image_hsv = cv2.cvtColor(np.array(image), cv2.COLOR_RGB2HSV)

        # Apply the color threshold to the image
        lower, upper = color_thresholds[target_color]
        mask = cv2.inRange(image_hsv, lower, upper)

        # Apply the mask to the target label region of the segmentation mask
        color_mask = np.zeros_like(pred_seg_np)
        color_mask[pred_seg_np ==
                   label_index] = mask[pred_seg_np == label_index]

        # Check if the color-filtered region constitutes a
        # certain percentage of the total region of the target label
        color_mask_percentage = np.sum(
            color_mask) / np.sum(pred_seg_np == label_index)

        if color_mask_percentage > required_percentage:
            # Display the original image, target label,
            # and the color filtered segmentation mask
            fig, ax = plt.subplots(1, 3, figsize=(12, 6))

            ax[0].imshow(image)
            ax[0].set_title('Original Image')
            ax[0].axis('off')

            ax[1].imshow(pred_seg_np)
            ax[1].set_title(f'{target_label} Segmentation')
            ax[1].axis('off')

            ax[2].imshow(color_mask)
            ax[2].set_title(
                f'{target_label} Segmentation Mask ({target_color})')
            ax[2].axis('off')

            plt.tight_layout()
            # Save the plot as an image file
            plt.savefig('data/segmentation.png')
            plt.close()
            


            # Append the file name to the list
            outputted_images.append(file_name)

numeric_values = []

for image_name in outputted_images:
    numeric_value = image_name.split("_")[1].split(".")[0]
    numeric_values.append(int(numeric_value))

Object (Person) Classification

Finally, using the results from the previous steps, I am able to successfully classify the person based on the specified parameters, such as the target label for object filtering, color filtering, and threshold. As a final step, I apply bounding boxes to the original photo to highlight the classified person.

  • The main image is displayed.
  • The code then iterates over each bounding box and its index from the bounding_boxes list:
    • If the index is included in the numeric_values list, the code proceeds to process the bounding box.
    • The bounding box values are converted to integers.
    • The positions of the label (x and y coordinates) are calculated based on the bounding box values. If the y coordinate is less than 0, it's set to 0 to ensure the label isn't drawn outside the image.
    • A label text is created, containing the target label and target color, and is displayed using matplotlib.pyplot.text. A box is drawn around the label text, using the bbox property to specify its style, face color (red), and transparency (alpha).
    • A rectangle is drawn around the bounding box using matplotlib.patches.Rectangle, with a line width of 3, edge color of green, and no fill color. This rectangle is then added to the axes using matplotlib.axes.Axes.add_patch.
  • The axes are then turned off using matplotlib.axes.Axes.axis('off') to ensure a clean image display without any axis lines or labels.
  • The layout is adjusted using matplotlib.pyplot.tight_layout to ensure the subplots do not overlap.
  • The updated image is then displayed.

for i, box in enumerate(bounding_boxes):
    if i in numeric_values:
        # Convert box values to integers
        box = [int(coord) for coord in box]

        # Calculate label position
        label_x = box[0]
        label_y = box[1] - 10
        if label_y < 0:
            label_y = 0

        # Add a text label to the box with background color and transparency
        label_text = f"{target_label} : {target_color}"
        bbox_props = dict(boxstyle='square,pad=0.1',
                          facecolor='red', alpha=0.5)

                 color='white', fontsize=15, bbox=bbox_props)

        specific_bbox_color = 'green'

            (box[0], box[1]), box[2]-box[0], box[3]-box[1],
            linewidth=3, edgecolor=specific_bbox_color, facecolor='none')
